SIMPLE: succeed
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Succeed
<hw>Suc*ceed"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Succeeded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Succeeding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>succedere</ets>,
<ets>successum</ets>; <ets>sub</ets> under + <ets>cedere</ets> to go, to
go along, approach, follow, succeed: cf. F. <ets>succ⟦eacute⟧der</ets>.
See <er>Cede</er>, and cf. <er>Success</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
follow in order; to come next after; hence, to take the place of;
<as>as, the king's eldest son <ex>succeeds</ex> his father on the
throne; autumn <ex>succeeds</ex> summer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As he saw him nigh <qex>succeed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fall heir to; to inherit.</def> <mark>[Obs. &
R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To come after; to be subsequent or consequent to; to
follow; to pursue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Destructive effects . . . <qex>succeeded</qex> the curse.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To support; to prosper; to promote.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Succeed</qex> my wish and second my design.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Succeed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Succeed
<hw>Suc*ceed"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To come in the
place of another person, thing, or event; to come next in the usual,
natural, or prescribed course of things; to follow; hence, to come next
in the possession of anything; -- often with <xex>to</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the father left only daughters, they equally
<qex>succeeded</qex> to him in copartnership.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M.
Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Enjoy till I return⟦br⟧
Short pleasures; for long woes are to <qex>succeed</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>To ascend the throne
after the removal the death of the occupant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No woman shall <qex>succeed</qex> in Salique land.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To descend, as an estate or an heirloom, in the same
family; to devolve.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To obtain the object desired; to accomplish what is
attempted or intended; to have a prosperous issue or termination; to be
successful; <as>as, he <ex>succeeded</ex> in his plans; his plans
<ex>succeeded</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is almost impossible for poets to <qex>succeed</qex> without
ambition.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spenser endeavored it in Shepherd's Kalendar; but neither will it
<qex>succeed</qex> in English.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To go under cover.</def> <mark>[A latinism.
Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will you to the cooler cave <qex>succeed</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To follow; pursue. See <er>Follow</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Succeedant</ent>⟦br⟧
